glosse of wealth and felicitee, whiche the state of a great
lorde or counsailour in a commen wealth dooeth outwardly
represent, did inwardly marke the trauailes,
cares, and anxietees, whiche suche one is driuen to susteigne
(doyng as he ought to dooe) in seruyng his maister
and countrey, wherby he is nothyng lesse than his
owne man: now I beleue he would not muche enuie his
state, nor chose to chaunge condicions of life with hym.
But this were euin the chiefest poincte of wysedome,

though fooles (as Folie calleth theim) that is to saie
vulgare folke, are those, that vnwittyng of their treasure,
dooe in deede enioie this sweete quietnesse, and
greatest good tourne. And waiyng this foolishe 
